04164nam a22006015i 9780292796294DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212006txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927962947 a10.7560/7094782doi  a(DE-B1597)587085  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aDS70b.B37 2005eb 7aSOC0030002bisacsh04a935/.0072/05692221 aBernhardsson, Magnus T., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReclaiming a Plundered Past :bArchaeology and Nation Building in Modern Iraq /cMagnus T. Bernhardsson. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2006  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER ONE Early Excavations in Mesopotamia -- tCHAPTER TWO World War I and the British Occupation (1900–1921) -- tCHAPTER THREE From Mesopotamia to Iraq: Politics during the Mandate (1921–1932) -- tCHAPTER FOUR Mandated Archaeology: The Creation of the Museum and the Vibrant Archaeological Scene (1921–1932) -- tCHAPTER FIVE Independent Nation—Independent Archaeology (1932–1941) -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tWorks Consulted -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe looting of the Iraqi National Museum in April of 2003 provoked a world outcry at the loss of artifacts regarded as part of humanity's shared cultural patrimony. But though the losses were unprecedented in scale, the museum looting was hardly the first time that Iraqi heirlooms had been plundered or put to political uses. From the beginning of archaeology as a modern science in the nineteenth century, Europeans excavated and appropriated Iraqi antiquities as relics of the birth of Western civilization. Since Iraq was created in 1921, the modern state has used archaeology to forge a connection to the ancient civilizations of Mesopotamia and/or Islamic empires and so build a sense of nationhood among Iraqis of differing religious traditions and ethnicities. This book delves into the ways that archaeology and politics intertwined in Iraq during the British Mandate and the first years of nationhood before World War II. Magnus Bernhardsson begins with the work of British archaeologists who conducted extensive excavations in Iraq and sent their finds to the museums of Europe. He then traces how Iraqis' growing sense of nationhood led them to confront the British over antiquities law and the division of archaeological finds between Iraq and foreign excavators. He shows how Iraq's control over its archaeological patrimony was directly tied to the balance of political power and how it increased as power shifted to the Iraqi government. Finally he examines how Iraqi leaders, including Saddam Hussein, have used archaeology and history to legitimize the state and its political actions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aExcavations (Archaeology)zIraqxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292796294423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292796294/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK